<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. TO REQUEST INTERNATIONAL FUNDING TO DEFUSE LAND MINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Clinton Administration will lead a worldwide fund-raising effort to get 
rid of land mines that kill or maim an estimated an 1,200 civilians each month. 
</P>
<P>
 Mines built to injure or kill humans cost as little as $3 to make and as much 
as $1,000 to find and defuse, and tens of millions of them are hidden around 
the world, witnesses told a Senate panel Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 "Land mines pose a significant impediment to achieving our foreign policy 
objectives in many regions of the world," said Thomas E. McNamara, deputy 
assistant secretary of state for political-military affairs, at a hearing 
billed as the first congressional inquiry into the problems. 
</P>
<P>
 McNamara said land mines prolong the bloodshed of conflicts, hinder refugee 
repatriation efforts and pollute land that might otherwise be productive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
